1. In the original logic [e.read().decode()](https://github.com/codalab/codalab-worksheets/blob/master/codalab/worker/bundle_service_client.py#L25), `e.read()` was treated as a bytes object that can be decoded. However, in Python3, `e.read()` actually returns a string object which doesn't have `decode()` function. This is where the error `AttributeError: 'str' object has no attribute 'decode'` was coming from. So I removed the `decode()` method.
2. Since `e.read()` will return a plain string in Python3 now, the structure of parsing object `urllib.error.HTTPError` changed quite a lot comparing with the original way. The original `client_error` will return something similar to ```{
    "error": "bad client",
    "msg": "error message"
}```
However, right now, `e.read()` will directly return the error message. I think it might not be necessary to convert it back and forth between a json object and string. (But I am open to discuss this, as one benefit from `json.dumps` is that it can ensure all the characters are ASCII encoded.)

