I studied your link more carefully and think my post above missed your point.  Studying it further, I agree now that the following would work under C++11:
```
std::string GetCompileLog(nvrtcProgram program) {
  size_t log_size_including_null;
  NVRTC_CALL(nvrtcGetProgramLogSize(program, &log_size_including_null));
  std::string log(log_size_including_null-1, '\0');
  // Room for terminating null character ensured since C++11
  NVRTC_CALL(nvrtcGetProgramLog(program, &log[0]));
  return log;
}
```
I guess with the version currently in the PR, I was being conservative, not wanting to research the level of C++11 support in all the compilers MXNet was going to see.  Do you see any difference between &log[0] and log.data() in terms of ensuring the compiler adheres to its contract of providing size()+1 bytes of contiguous storage?

